<subSubSection id="8FCC6574FF8C342FFF590382FEF9D3B1" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="2" pageId="2" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph id="C76936FFFF8C342EFF590382FE65D6D5" blockId="2.[192,664,1733,1791]" box="[192,348,1766,1791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1">
(
<figureCitation id="5FED2A7AFF8C342EFF510382FE6BD6D5" box="[200,338,1766,1791]" captionStart="Figure 1-10" captionStartId="12.[192,276,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[229,1385,231,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[215,1421,192,1841]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 1-10. Hyperaspis corcovado. 1-4) Habitus views. 5) Abdomen. 6-9) Male genitalia. 6) Sipho. 7) Enlarged siphonal apex. 8-9) Lateral and ventral views of phallobase. 10) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5160408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5160408/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="1">Figure 1-10</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C76936FFFF8C342FFF590242FEA9D371" blockId="2.[192,1440,1830,1886]" lastBlockId="3.[192,1441,195,859]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="2" pageId="2" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8C342EFF590242FE55D714" bold="true" box="[192,364,1830,1854]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1">Description.</emphasis>
Male 
<typeStatus id="186D885DFF8C342EFE250242FD13D714" box="[444,554,1830,1854]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1">holotype</typeStatus>
. Length 3.0 mm, width 
<quantity id="002E9B1AFF8C342EFCC10243FC80D714" box="[856,953,1831,1855]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="2" pageNumber="1" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
. Body weakly elongate, convex. Dorsal surface with head alutaceous, feebly shiny, pronotum weakly alutaceous, slightly shiny, elytron smooth, shiny. Color reddish yellow except head yellow; pronotum with narrow, basal black macula apically emarginate; elytron with sutural border narrowly black, black area slightly widened medially, median, curved vitta present from base across humeral callus to sutural margin at apical 1/6 (
<figureCitation id="5FED2A7AFF8D342FFB4E0467FA0CD131" box="[1239,1333,259,283]" captionStart="Figure 1-10" captionStartId="12.[192,276,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[229,1385,231,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[215,1421,192,1841]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 1-10. Hyperaspis corcovado. 1-4) Habitus views. 5) Abdomen. 6-9) Male genitalia. 6) Sipho. 7) Enlarged siphonal apex. 8-9) Lateral and ventral views of phallobase. 10) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5160408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5160408/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1-4</figureCitation>
); base of head, prosternum, meso- and metaventrites black; abdomen dark brown medially, dark reddish brown laterally. Head punctures small, separated by a diameter or less; pronotal punctures larger than on head, separated by a diameter or less; elytral punctures slightly larger than on pronotum, separated by a diameter or less; punctures on metaventrite very large, separated by a diameter or less medially, becoming larger and nearly contiguous in lateral 1/4; punctures on basal abdominal ventrite large medially, separated by a diameter or less, becoming smaller, more scattered in lateral 1/3, punctures on sternites 2- 6 fine, sparse, separated by a diameter or less. Clypeal apex deeply emarginate, clypeus and frons joined at abrupt angle. Epipleuron wide, grooved medially, descending externally, femoral depressions deep. Antenna with 10 articles (
<figureCitation id="5FED2A7AFF8D342FFE6E0747FD72D211" box="[503,587,547,571]" captionStart="Figure 1-10" captionStartId="12.[192,276,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[229,1385,231,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[215,1421,192,1841]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 1-10. Hyperaspis corcovado. 1-4) Habitus views. 5) Abdomen. 6-9) Male genitalia. 6) Sipho. 7) Enlarged siphonal apex. 8-9) Lateral and ventral views of phallobase. 10) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5160408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5160408/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Protibia narrow, slightly flanged. Prosternum with intercoxal carinae widely separated at apex, convergent toward base, joined at basal 2/3, connected to base by single stem. Postcoxal line on basal abdominal ventrite straight in basal 1/3, flattened along posterior margin of ventrite, rounded 5/6 distance to lateral margin (
<figureCitation id="5FED2A7AFF8D342FFD6007E7FC04D2B1" box="[761,829,643,667]" captionStart="Figure 1-10" captionStartId="12.[192,276,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[229,1385,231,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[215,1421,192,1841]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 1-10. Hyperaspis corcovado. 1-4) Habitus views. 5) Abdomen. 6-9) Male genitalia. 6) Sipho. 7) Enlarged siphonal apex. 8-9) Lateral and ventral views of phallobase. 10) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5160408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5160408/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Fifth ventrite broadly, deeply emarginate apically; 6 
<superScript id="30A39BB7FF8D342FFF5607C5FFE7D285" attach="left" box="[207,222,673,687]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">th</superScript>
ventrite with broad, shallow apical emargination. Genitalia with basal lobe 2/3 length of paramere, narrow basally, strongly widened to truncate apex, one lateral margin sinuate with small, median projection; paramere elongate, slender, slightly tapered from base to apex; trabes long, apically curved laterally (
<figureCitation id="5FED2A7AFF8D342FFF500667FE12D331" box="[201,299,771,795]" captionStart="Figure 1-10" captionStartId="12.[192,276,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[229,1385,231,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[215,1421,192,1841]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 1-10. Hyperaspis corcovado. 1-4) Habitus views. 5) Abdomen. 6-9) Male genitalia. 6) Sipho. 7) Enlarged siphonal apex. 8-9) Lateral and ventral views of phallobase. 10) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5160408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5160408/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 8, 9</figureCitation>
); sipho long, curved in basal 3/4, basal capsule long, enlarged, inner arm long, narrow basally, widened apically, outer arm short, nearly absent, rectangular, abruptly bent, basal border widely emarginate (
<figureCitation id="5FED2A7AFF8D342FFE840627FEBBD371" box="[285,386,835,859]" captionStart="Figure 1-10" captionStartId="12.[192,276,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[229,1385,231,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-24@12.[215,1421,192,1841]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 1-10. Hyperaspis corcovado. 1-4) Habitus views. 5) Abdomen. 6-9) Male genitalia. 6) Sipho. 7) Enlarged siphonal apex. 8-9) Lateral and ventral views of phallobase. 10) Antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5160408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5160408/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 6, 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C76936FFFF8D342FFF5906E7FEF9D3B1" blockId="3.[192,448,899,923]" box="[192,448,899,923]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8D342FFF5906E7FE1CD3B1" bold="true" box="[192,293,899,923]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Female</emphasis>
. Not known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
